The '''British Video Association''' ('''BVA''') is a video home entertainment organisation established in 1980. Its members include the [[BBC]] and [[Cinema of the United States|Hollywood studios]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Broadband providers under pressure to clamp down on illegal downloads |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/news/10281365/Broadband-providers-under-pressure-to-clamp-down-on-illegal-downloads.html |author=Sophie Curtis |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=2 September 2013 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> The Association organises an annual awards ceremony (The ''BVA Awards'') in London.<ref>{{cite web|title= BVA Awards 2013|url=http://www.eraltd.org/news/industry-news/bva-awards-2013.aspx|publisher=Entertainment Retail Association|accessdate=9 January 2014}}</ref> In 2003, the BVA reported a 61% increase of [[DVD]] sales alongside a tripling in the illegal downloading of [[film]] and [[television]] files.<ref>{{cite news|title=Internet piracy figures 'triple'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/3692999.stm|publisher=BBC News|date=7 May 2004}}</ref> In 2010 the Association publicised the fact that around six million people in the UK have failed to acquire a [[HDTV|High Definition]] signal for [[HD ready]] [[Television set]]s.<ref>{{cite web|title=Six million people in the UK miss out on HD TV|url=http://hdtvorg.co.uk/news/articles/2010040901.htm|publisher=HDTVorg|date=9 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Sara Nathan|title=Highly difficult: How millions have bought a high definition TV ... but don't have a clue how to make it work properly|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1264671/HD-TV-How-millions-dont-clue-make-work-properly.html|publisher=Mail Online|date=9 April 2010}}</ref>
