{{Infobox person | image = | image_size = | name = Dmitri Lebedev | caption = | birth_name = Dmitri Alexeyevich Lebedev | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1968|03|30|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Leningrad]], [[Soviet Union]] (now St Petersburg, Russia) | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | restingplace = | nationality = | religion = | ethnicity = | residence = | education = | alma mater = | occupation = Chairman of the Board of Directors and shareholder, [[Rossiya Bank]] | known for = | salary = | networth = | spouse = | parents = | children = | relatives = | website = |awards = }}
'''Dmitri Alekseevich Lebedev''' ({{lang-ru|Дмитрий Алексеевич Лебедев}}, born March 30, 1968) is a Russian businessman and financier.
==Education== Lebedev graduated from the [[Saint Petersburg State University of Economics and Finance|Leningrad Financial and Economic Institute (LFEI)]] majoring in economics in 1992 and received his [[master's degree]] in economics from LFEI in 1997.<ref name=FinParty>{{cite web | title = Биография — Дмитрий Лебедев | url = https://finparty.ru/personal/dmitriy-lebedev/ | publisher = Fin Party | language = Russian | trans-title = Biography — Dmitry Lebedev | access-date = March 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=anticompromat>{{cite web | title = ЛЕБЕДЕВ Дмитрий Алексеевич | url = https://anticompromat.org/kovalch1/lebedev_dbio.html | publisher = Anticompromat | language = Russian | trans-title = Lebedev Dmitry Alekseevich | access-date = March 26, 2018}}</ref>
==Career== In 1988, Lebedev began his career as an economist at the Leningrad regional administration of [[:ru:Банк ВТБ Северо-Запад|Promstroibank USSR]] (Russian: Промстройбанка СССР){{efn|Before the Russian Revolution, this bank was the Volga-Kama Commercial Bank (Russian: Волжско-Камский коммерческий банк). After the revolution, the bank was reorganized several times: 1923 as the Petrograd Communal Bank (Russian: Петроградский коммунальный банк), 1959 as the Leningrad regional office of the Stroibank USSR (Russian: Стройбанка СССР), 1987 as the Leningrad Regional Administration of the Industrial and Construction Bank of the USSR (Russian: Промышленно-строительного банка СССР) and 1990 as the Leningrad Commercial Industrial and Construction Bank (Russian: Ленинградский коммерческий Промышленно-строительный банк). In 1997, Promstroybank became the first Russian bank to enter the United States market but Promstoybank was severely affected by the [[1998 Russian financial crisis|Russian financial crisis of the late 1990s]]. In April 2004, Bank Rossiya liquidated Promstoybank. In 2005, [[VTB Bank|Bank VTB]] acquired a majority stake of 75% plus three shares in Promstroybank and renamed Promstroibank ''Bank VTB North-West'', later becoming the VTB’s North-Western Regional Centre in March 2011.<ref name=spb>{{cite web | title = ОАО «Промышленно-строительный банк» | url = https://www.spb-business.ru/show.php?directory=60360 | publisher = PSB | language = Russian | trans-title = OJSC Industrial and Construction Bank | access-date = March 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=Promstroybank>{{cite web | last = Чаплыгина (Chaplygina) | first = Татьяна (Tatiana) | title = Миф о жертве кризиса: 400 млн. рублей могли спасти Промстройбанк России от ликвидации | url = https://bankir.ru/publikacii/20070622/mif-o-jertve-krizisa-1367244/ | publisher = bankir.ru | language = Russian | trans-title = Myth of the victim of the crisis: 400 million rubles could save Promstroybank of Russia from liquidation | date = June 22, 2007 | access-date = March 24, 2018}}</ref><ref name=szrcvtb>{{cite web | title = О Северо-Западном региональном центре | url = http://www.szrc.vtb.ru/o_szrc.html | archive-date = April 17, 2013 | archive-url = https://archive.is/ljIFG | language = Russian | trans-title = About the North-West Regional Center | publisher = ВТБ (VTB) | access-date = March 24, 2018}}</ref>}} in the [[Soviet Union]].<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=anticompromat/> From 1990-3, he worked at the Central Administration of the [[Central Bank of Russia]] in St. Petersburg.<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=anticompromat/> From 1993-5 he was both a director of the [[Rossiya Bank|Bank Rossiya]] (Russian: АКБ "Россия") in St. Petersburg under [[Yuri Kovalchuk]] and, from 1994-5, first deputy chairman of the board of the [[Viking Bank|CAB "Viking"]] (Russian: КАБ "Викинг") where Alexey Ustaev (Russian: Алексей Устаев) was the chairman of the board.<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=anticompromat/> He returned to the Central Directorate of the Central Bank for St. Petersburg from 1996-2000 and oversaw the technology department. Under the Chairman of the Board Vitaly Saveliev (Russian: Виталий Савельев) at [[Bank Menatep|JSCB "MENATEP - St. Petersburg"]] (Russian: банка "МЕНАТЕП-Санкт-Петербург"), he served as the Deputy Chairman (April 2000 to September 2001) and later as the Chairman of the Board (September 2001 to November 2003) being succeeded by Oleg Kolyada (Russian: Олег Коляда) in November 2003.<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=anticompromat/> In October 2003 at the investment bank Trust (Russian: "Траст"), he served on the board of directors.<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=anticompromat/> He advised Yuri Kraskovsky (Russian: Юрия Красковского), the president of Transcreditbank (Russian: Транскредитбанка), from April to August 2004.<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=anticompromat/> After that, he became an advisor to Yuri Kovalchuk, the Chairman of the Board of Directors at the Bank Rossiya.<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=anticompromat/> In December 2004, he was the director at the Center for Strategic Research - North-West Foundation (Kovalchuk Center) (Russian: Центра стратегического развития (ЦСР) "Северо-Запад" ("Центр Ковальчука") and from January 2005 until April 2006, he was the director at the Center for Strategic Research (CSR) "North-West" (Russian: Центр стратегических разработок ЦСР «Северо-Запад»).<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=anticompromat/>
===Bank of Rossiya=== From April 3, 2006, to June 2012, he was the CEO and Chairman of the Board of Bank Rossiya replacing Mikhail Klishin (Russian: Михаил Клишин), who became the First Deputy Chairman of the Board.<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=anticompromat/><ref name=BankRossiya>{{cite web | title = Совет Директоров | url = https://abr.ru/about/corp/corporativ/ | publisher = Bank Rossiya | language = Russian | trans-title = Board of Directors | access-date = March 26, 2018}}</ref><ref name=finnews060405>{{cite news | title = Генеральным директором банка "Россия" назначен Дмитрий Лебедев | url = https://www.finnews.ru/cur_new.php?idnws=2854 | publisher = FinNews.ru | language = Russian | trans-title = Dmitry Lebedev appointed CEO of Bank Rossiya | date = April 5, 2006 | access-date = March 26, 2018}}</ref> In June 2012, Evgeny Logovinsky (Russian: Евгению Логовинскому) took over Lebedev's post as CEO, and, since June 2012, Lebedev has been the Chairman of the Board of Directors of Bank Rossiya replacing Yuri Kovalchuk who had held that post for seven years.<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=anticompromat/><ref name=Kommersant120622>{{cite news | last1 = Kiseleva | first1 = Elena | last2 = Dementieva | first2 = Ksenia | title = Банкир в "России" — больше, чем банкир: Юрий Ковальчук нашел возможность для карьерного роста | url = https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/1963698 | publisher = Kommersant | language = Russian | trans-title = Banker in "Russia" - more than a banker: Yuri Kovalchuk found an opportunity for career growth | date = June 22, 2012 | access-date = March 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Дмитрий Алексеевич Лебедев | url = https://arb.ru/profile/lebedev-dmitriy-alekseevich-2905/ | publisher = Ассоциация российских банков (АРБ) | language = Russian | trans-title = Dmitry Alekseevich Lebedev | access-date = April 24, 2018}}</ref> He is a member of the Board of Directors of [[Tele2 Russia|Tele2]], which is part of the "T2 RTK Holding" LLC (Russian: ООО «Т2 РТК Холдинг»), and is the Managing Director of CJSC "ADB Management" (Russian: ЗАО «АБР Менеджмент») which oversees the strategic management of Bank Rossiya.<ref name=FinParty/><ref name=RBC170427>{{cite news | title = Tele2 утвердил новый совет директоров | url = https://www.rbc.ru/rbcfreenews/5901b7489a794752c4e3e67e | language = Russian | trans-title = Tele2 has approved a new board of directors | publisher = RBC | date = April 27, 2017 | access-date = May 7, 2018}}</ref>
On September 11, 2014, he became a 14.62% share holder of the Big House 9 (Russian: ООО "Большой дом 9") which is a co-owner of ABRos (Russian: ИК "Аброс"), the largest shareholder of [[SOGAZ]] (Russian: "СОГАЗа").<ref name=Interfax140922>{{cite news | title = Топ-менеджеры банка "Россия" вошли в число бенефициаров "Аброса" | url = http://www.interfax.ru/business/398025 | publisher = Interfax | location = Moscow | language = Russian | trans-title = Top-managers of the bank "Russia" were among the beneficiaries of "Abros" | date = September 22, 2014 | access-date = March 26, 2018}}</ref> The other share holders are Yuri Kovalchuk, (was 52.76% but became 29.63%), and Tatyana Kovalchuk (Russian: Татьяна Ковальчукa), (was 36.11% but became 20.27%), ex-RFU head Sergei Fursenko (Russian: Сергей Фурсенко), (was 11.1% but became 6.2%), who are all original owners; and new co-owners Yury Kovalchuk's nephew Kirill Kovalchuk (Russian: Кирилл Ковальчук), and Mikhail Klishin (Russian: Михаил Клишин) each with 14.62%.<ref name=Interfax140922/>
==Sanctions== {{main|International sanctions during the Ukrainian crisis}} On December 20, 2016, the [[US Treasury Department]] sanctioned Lebedev pursuant to [[s:Executive Order 13661|EO 13661]] for providing support to senior officials of the Russian Federation.<ref name=Ukraine-EO13661>{{cite web | last = President of The United States | title = Ukraine EO13661 | url = https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/ukraine_eo2.pdf | publisher = Federal Register | date = March 19, 2016 | accessdate = February 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=US161220>{{cite web |url=https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20161220.aspx |title=Russia/Ukraine-related Designations and Identifications; Publication of Russia/Ukraine-related General License |publisher= treasury.gov |date= 20 December 2016 }}</ref><ref name=OFAC161220>{{cite web|url=https://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/jl0688.aspx|title=Treasury Sanctions Individuals and Entities In Connection with Russia's Occupation of Crimea and the Conflict in Ukraine|website=U.S. Department of the Treasury|date=December 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/20/world/europe/us-blacklists-15-russian-entities-linked-to-ukraine-and-crimea.html | title = U.S. Blacklists 15 Russian Entities Linked to Ukraine and Crimea | last = Landler | first = Mark | author-link = Mark Landler | newspaper = New York Times | date = December 20, 2016 | access-date = April 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://tass.com/world/921040 | title = United States widen sanctions against Russia: Nine regional units of Russian gas producer Novatek are now in the sanction list | agency = TASS | date = December 20, 2016 | access-date = April 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.unian.info/politics/1689406-us-sanctions-seven-individuals-eight-entities-over-crimea-occupation.html | title = U.S. sanctions seven individuals, eight entities over Crimea occupation | agency = UNIAN | date = December 20, 2016 | access-date = April 24, 2018}}</ref>
