'''Emilio T. Yap''', [[Philippine Legion of Honor|GCLH]] (September 24, 1925 – April 7, 2014) was a [[Chinese Filipino]] business tycoon. He was the chairman of the board of the ''[[Manila Bulletin]]''.
==Birthplace== Yap, who was of Chinese descent, was born on September 24, 1925.<ref name=pstar/> He began his business career in 1942.<ref name=pstar/>
==Later years== In July 1984, Yap was elected as the chairman of the board of the ''[[Manila Bulletin]]'', a position he held until his death in 2014.<ref name=gma>{{cite news|first=|last=|title=Manila Bulletin chairman Don Emilio Yap passes away |url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/355851/lifestyle/peopleandevents/manila-bulletin-chairman-don-emilio-yap-passes-away |work=[[GMA News]] |publisher= |date=2014-04-07 |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> He was also the vice president of the executive department of the ''Manila Bulletin''.<ref name=gma/> Additionally, Yap was the chairman of [[Manila Hotel]] from 1997 until 2014, chairman of [[Centro Escolar University]] since 2002, and the chairman emeritus of [[Philtrust Bank]].<ref name=pstar>{{cite news|first=Charmie Joy |last=Pagulong|title=Emilio Yap, 88 |url=http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2014/04/08/1310056/emilio-yap-88 |work=[[Philippine Star]] |publisher= |date=2014-04-08 |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref><ref name=gma/> ''[[Forbes]]'' ranked Yap as the 15th wealthiest person in the Philippines in 2013, with an estimated net worth of $1.1&nbsp;billion.<ref name=pstar/><ref name=gma/>
==Death== Yap died on April 7, 2014, at the age of 88.<ref name=gma/>
