{{Expand Spanish|topic=gov|date=February 2017}} {{spanish name|Lasso|Mendoza}} {{Infobox officeholder |name = Guillermo Lasso |office = Superminister of Economy |image = Guillermo Lasso perfil vertical.jpg |predecessor = ''Position established'' |president = [[Jamil Mahuad]] |successor = ''Position abolished'' |party = [[Creating Opportunities]] |office1 = Governor of [[Guayas Province|Guayas]] |predecessor1 = Rafael Guerrero Valenzuela |successor1 = Benjamín Rosales Valenzuela |birth_name = Guillermo Alberto Santiago Lasso Mendoza |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1955|11|16|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Guayaquil]], [[Ecuador]] |death_date = |death_place = |spouse = María de Lourdes Alcívar Crespo |children = 5 |website = {{url|guillermolasso.ec|Official website}} |term_start = 17 August 1999 |term_end = 24 September 1999 |term_start1 = 10 August 1998 |term_end1 = 17 August 1999 }} '''Guillermo Alberto Santiago Lasso Mendoza''' (born 16 November 1955) is an [[Ecuador]]ian businessman and politician. In the [[Ecuadorian general election, 2013]] he was presidential candidate for the party [[Creating Opportunities]].<ref name=creo>[http://www.ecuadortimes.net/2012/11/14/creo-enrolled-lasso-solines-binomial/ CREO enrolled Lasso-Solines binomial]</ref><ref>"In that case the opposition should unite around a single candidate who, according to ARCOP, would be Guillermo Lasso, with 26% of voter preference in the same survey." [http://www.ecuadortimes.net/2013/02/04/correas-reelection-is-uncertain/ Correa’s reelection is uncertain]</ref> He landed in second place with 22.68% of valid votes but as incumbent President [[Rafael Correa]] received more than double that amount, namely 57.17%. Lasso is, through a trust named with his initials, GLM, the largest share holder in Banco de Guayaquil, where he has been executive president for more than 20 years.<ref>Mark Weisbrot: [http://thehill.com/blogs/pundits-blog/international/325442-media-cant-ignore-financial-scandal-in-ecuadors-presidential Media can't ignore financial scandal in Ecuador's presidential election], TheHill, 24. March 2017</ref>
In early 2017, Lasso launched his second presidential campaign to succeed incumbent President Correa for the conservative [[Creating Opportunities]] party in the [[Ecuadorian general election, 2017|2017 presidential elections]], as Correa had already served his two-term constitutionally defined limit. His campaign's theme was one of "change" and he pledged to create one million more jobs in Ecuador.<ref>[http://www.ecuadorinmediato.com/index.php?module=Noticias&func=news_user_view&id=2818813638&umt=guillermo_lasso_inicia_su_campaf1a_electoral_visitando_puerta_a_puerta_a_ciudadanos_en_guayaquil Guillermo Lasso inicia su campaña electoral visitando puerta a puerta a ciudadanos en Guayaquil], ecuadorinmediato.com, 2017-01-03 (Spanish)</ref> Lasso received 48.84% and lost to [[Lenín Moreno]].<ref>[http://www.telesurtv.net/english/news/Ecuadors-Right-Wing-Opposition-Doesnt-Show-Up-to-Public-Recount-it-Demanded-20170418-0015.html Lenin Again Wins Ecuador's Presidential Race After Recount], teleSUR English, 18 April 2017</ref>
In February 2017, Lasso said in an interview with a British newspaper that in case of his victory in the presidential election he would “cordially ask” [[Julian Assange]], the [[WikiLeaks]] founder, to leave the Ecuadorian Embassy in London within 30 days.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/feb/09/ecuador-julian-assange-embassy-notice-eviction Ecuador presidential hopeful promises to evict Julian Assange from embassy], The Guardian, 9. February 2017</ref>
According to information from the Inspectorate of Banks of [[Panamá]], revealed by the Argentine newspaper [[Página 12]], Guillermo Lasso is associated with forty-nine offshore companies located in tax havens. His fortune would have jumped from $1 million to $31 million between 1999 and 2002, after his brief passage to the government.<ref>https://www.pagina12.com.ar/25889-lasso-el-magnate-de-las-offshore</ref>
